Introduction to Data Visualization in R

Getting Started with Plotting in R

Above all else show the data. Edward Tufte

Visualizing data is one of the most important tasks in data analysis. This notebook will introduce you to basic plotting in R using simple examples.

Your First Plot

Lets start by creating a simple vector and plotting it. Well use the Fibonacci sequence as our example:

# Create a vector with the first 7 Fibonacci numbers
Fibonacci <- c(1, 1, 2, 3, 5, 8, 13)

# Plot them
plot(Fibonacci)

What R has done here is plot the values from the Fibonacci vector on the vertical axis (y-axis) and the corresponding index on the horizontal axis (x-axis). Since the 4th element has a value of 3, we get a dot at location (4, 3).

Customizing Titles and Labels

One of the first things youll want to do is add proper labels to your plot:

plot(x = Fibonacci,
     main = "The First 7 Fibonacci Numbers",
     xlab = "Position in the Sequence",
     ylab = "The Fibonacci Number")

The key arguments here are: - main: The title of the plot - xlab: The x-axis label - ylab: The y-axis label

Changing Plot Types

The type argument lets you change how the data is displayed:

# Points only (default)
plot(Fibonacci, type = "p", main = "type = 'p' (points)")

# Lines only
plot(Fibonacci, type = "l", main = "type = 'l' (lines)")

# Both points and lines
plot(Fibonacci, type = "b", main = "type = 'b' (both)")

# Lines over points
plot(Fibonacci, type = "o", main = "type = 'o' (overplotted)")

Customizing Plot Appearance

You can customize colors, point styles, line types, and more:

plot(Fibonacci,
     type = "b",           # both points and lines
     col = "blue",         # color
     pch = 19,            # solid circles
     lwd = 2,             # line width
     main = "Customized Fibonacci Plot",
     xlab = "Position",
     ylab = "Value")

Key customization arguments: - col: Color of points/lines - pch: Point character (1-25 for different symbols) - lwd: Line width - lty: Line type (1=solid, 2=dashed, 3=dotted, etc.)

Histograms

Histograms are great for understanding the distribution of your data. Lets create some simulated data:

# Simulate 200 test scores (normally distributed around 75)
set.seed(123)
test_scores <- rnorm(200, mean = 75, sd = 10)

par(lwd = 3)
# Draw a histogram
hist(test_scores,
     main = "Distribution of Test Scores",
     xlab = "Score",
     col = "lightblue",
     border = "darkblue",
     lwd = 2)

Boxplots

Boxplots show the median, quartiles, and potential outliers in your data:

# Create simulated data for three different groups
set.seed(456)
group_A <- rnorm(50, mean = 70, sd = 8)
group_B <- rnorm(50, mean = 75, sd = 10)
group_C <- rnorm(50, mean = 80, sd = 9)

# Combine into a data frame
data <- data.frame(
  score = c(group_A, group_B, group_C),
  group = rep(c("A", "B", "C"), each = 50)
)

# Draw boxplots
boxplot(score ~ group, 
        data = data,
        main = "Test Scores by Group",
        xlab = "Group",
        ylab = "Score",
        col = c("lightblue", "lightgreen", "lightpink"))

The thick line in each box shows the median. The box spans from the 25th to 75th percentile, and the whiskers extend to show the range of the data (excluding outliers).

Scatterplots

Scatterplots show the relationship between two variables:

# Simulate data: hours studied vs. test score
set.seed(789)
hours_studied <- runif(50, min = 0, max = 10)
test_score <- 50 + 4 * hours_studied + rnorm(50, mean = 0, sd = 5)

# Draw scatterplot
plot(x = hours_studied,
     y = test_score,
     main = "Test Score vs. Hours Studied",
     xlab = "Hours Studied",
     ylab = "Test Score",
     pch = 19,
     col = adjustcolor("blue", alpha.f = 0.6),
     cex = 1.5,
     cex.lab = 1.3,    # Increase axis label size
     cex.main = 1.5,   # Increase title size
     cex.axis = 1.2)

# Add a trend line
abline(lm(test_score ~ hours_studied), col = "black", lwd = 2, lty=2)

Bar Plots

Bar plots are useful for categorical data:

# Simulate survey responses
set.seed(321)
responses <- sample(c("Strongly Disagree", "Disagree", "Neutral", 
                      "Agree", "Strongly Agree"), 
                   100, replace = TRUE,
                   prob = c(0.1, 0.15, 0.2, 0.35, 0.2))

# Create a frequency table
freq_table <- table(responses)

par(lwd = 2)
# Draw bar plot
barplot(freq_table,
        main = "Survey Responses",
        ylab = "Frequency",
        col = adjustcolor("blue", alpha.f = 0.6), 
        border = "black",  # Border color
        las = 2, # Rotate labels
        lwd = 2)

Multiple Plots in One Figure

You can arrange multiple plots in a grid:

# Set up a 2x2 grid of plots
par(mfrow = c(2, 2))

# Plot 1: Line plot
plot(Fibonacci, type = "l", main = "Line Plot", col = "blue", lwd = 2)

# Plot 2: Histogram
hist(test_scores, main = "Histogram", col = "lightgreen")

# Plot 3: Line plot
plot(Fibonacci, type = "o", main = "Line Plot 2", col = "red", lwd = 3)

# Plot 4: Scatterplot
plot(hours_studied, test_score, main = "Scatterplot", pch = 19, col = "purple")

# Reset to single plot
par(mfrow = c(1, 1))

Key Takeaways

  1. plot() is the basic function for creating plots in R
  2. Use type to change between points, lines, or both
  3. Customize with col, pch, lwd, and other parameters
  4. Specialized functions include:
    • hist() for histograms
    • boxplot() for boxplots
    • barplot() for bar charts
  5. Always add clear labels with main, xlab, and ylab
